{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480523"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:45:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:45:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"63"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"63","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/63"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.17,0.01,0.62,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"63"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76421"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"63","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/63"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"63"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61918"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2349"},{"type":"tags","id":"2967"},{"type":"tags","id":"4689"},{"type":"tags","id":"4890"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"6344"},{"type":"tags","id":"6486"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"516"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1723"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42957"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44610"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76421"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of increasing urinary incontinence. She reports urgency and increased frequency, needing to toilet 8-10 times per day without nocturia. She feels she completely empties her bladder each time. The incontinence is not exacerbated by coughing or laughing but occurs when walking upstairs to reach the bathroom or hearing running water. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has type 2 diabetes mellitus and osteoarthritis of the left knee. Her regular medications include metformin and paracetamol. She drinks 1.5 L of fluids daily. She has had one pregnancy delivered via caesarean section. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Pelvic examination reveals no prolapse. The cough stress test is negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pelvic floor exercises","Oxybutynin","Sacral nerve stimulation","Bladder diary and retraining exercises","Restrict fluids to 1 L/day"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of urge urinary incontinence, with no features of stress incontinence. The symptoms of urgency, frequency, and triggers such as running water or approaching the toilet are characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBladder diary and retraining exercises\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial management. Bladder retraining aims to reduce voiding frequency and modify bladder function through scheduled voiding rather than responding to urgency. This behavioural intervention should be tried for at least six weeks before considering other treatments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPelvic floor exercises\u003C/strong\u003E are first-line treatment for stress urinary incontinence, which is characterised by leakage with coughing or physical exertion. This patient\u0027s history and negative cough stress test make stress incontinence unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxybutynin\u003C/strong\u003E and other anticholinergic medications can be effective but are not first-line treatment due to side effects. They should be considered only if behavioural interventions fail to provide adequate relief.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESacral nerve stimulation\u003C/strong\u003E is a surgical intervention reserved for refractory cases that have failed conservative and medical management. It would be inappropriate as initial management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERestricting fluids\u003C/strong\u003E to 1 L/day is not recommended and may be harmful. Management should focus on reducing potential bladder irritants like caffeine and alcohol rather than restricting total fluid intake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMultiple studies have shown that behavioural therapy, alone or combined with other interventions, is generally more effective than pharmacological therapies alone for urge incontinence. The focus should be on modifying voiding habits before considering medication or invasive treatments.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bladder retraining is first-line management for urge urinary incontinence, before considering pharmacological therapy.","Urge incontinence typically presents with urgency, frequency and leakage triggered by running water or approaching the toilet.","Behavioural therapy is more effective than medications alone in treating urge incontinence."],"references":["Aoki Y, Brown HW, Brubaker L, Cornu JN, Daly JO, Cartwright R. Urinary incontinence in women. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2017 Jul 6;3:17042. doi: 10.1038/nrdp.2017.42. Erratum in: Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2017 Nov 16;3:17097. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28681849/","Burgio KL. Current perspectives on management of urgency using bladder and behavioural training. J Am Acad Nurse Pract 2004;16(10 Suppl):4. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15543926/","Balk EM, Rofeberg VN, Gaelen PA, et al. Pharmacologic and Nonpharmacologic Treatments for Urinary Incontinence in Women: A Systematic Review and Network Meta-analysis of Clinical Outcomes. Ann Int Med 2019; 170: 465-79. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30884526/","The Royal Australian College of General Practitioners; Aged Care Clinical Guideline (Silver book), Part A; Urinary Incontinenc [online] 5th edition. EastMelbourne (AU). 2023 [cited 2023 June 25]. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/silver-book/part-a/urinary-incontinence"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61918"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"63"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61918"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T13:47:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T13:47:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"63"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76421"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/ap